# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: next-gen-firewall
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] An **Internet filter** is a type of Internet censorship that restricts or controls the content an Internet user is capable to access, especially when utilized to restrict material delivered over the Internet via the Web, Email, or other means.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] The motive is often to prevent access to content which the computer's owner(s) or other authorities may consider objectionable.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] When imposed without the consent of the user, content control can be characterised as a form of internet censorship.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] Some filter software includes time control functions that empowers parents to set the amount of time that child may spend accessing the Internet or playing games or other computer activities.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] The term "content control" is used on occasion by CNN, *Playboy* magazine, the *San Francisco Chronicle*, and *The New York Times*.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] However, several other terms, including "content filtering software", "web content filter", "filtering proxy servers", "secure web gateways", "censorware", "content security and control", "web filtering software", "content-censoring software", and "content-blocking software", are often used.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] "Nannyware" has also been used in both product marketing and by the media.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] Industry research company Gartner uses **"secure web gateway"** (SWG) to describe the market segment.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] Some products log all sites that a user accesses and rates them based on content type for reporting to an "accountability partner" of the person's choosing, and the term accountability software is used.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] Internet filters, parental control software, and/or accountability software may also be combined into one product.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] Those critical of such software, however, use the term "censorware" freely: consider the Censorware Project, for example.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] Filters can be implemented in many different ways: by software on a personal computer, via network infrastructure such as proxy servers, DNS servers, or firewalls that provide Internet access.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] No solution provides complete coverage, so most companies deploy a mix of technologies to achieve the proper content control in line with their policies.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] E-mail filters act on information contained in the mail body, in the mail headers such as sender and subject, and e-mail attachments to classify, accept, or reject messages.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] , a type of statistical filter, are commonly used.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] Both client and server based filters are available.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] This type of filter is installed as software on each computer where filtering is required.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] This filter can typically be managed, disabled or uninstalled by anyone who has administrator-level privileges on the system.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] Content-limited (or filtered) ISPs are Internet service providers that offer access to only a set portion of Internet content on an opt-in or a mandatory basis.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] Anyone who subscribes to this type of service is subject to restrictions.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] functionality to filter outbound as well as inbound information.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] All users are subject to the access policy defined by the institution.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] The filtering can be customized, so a school district's high school library can have a different filtering profile than the district's junior high school library.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] This type of filtering is implemented at the DNS layer and attempts to prevent lookups for domains that do not fit within a set of policies (either parental control or company rules).
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] offer filtering options as part of their services.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] can be also be used for this purpose, though client-side only.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] offer users the option of turning on a safety filter.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] When this safety filter is activated, it filters out the inappropriate links from all of the search results.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] If users know the actual URL of a website that features explicit or adult content, they have the ability to access that content without using a search engine.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] Some providers offer child-oriented versions of their engines that permit only child friendly websites.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] Some offer security software which includes parental controls.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] operating system also includes content-control software.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] The Internet does not intrinsically provide content blocking, and therefore there is much content on the Internet that is considered unsuitable for children, given that much content is given certifications as suitable for adults only, e.g.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] Internet service providers (ISPs) that block material containing pornography, or controversial religious, political, or news-related content en route are often utilized by parents who do not permit their children to access content not conforming to their personal beliefs.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] Content filtering software can, however, also be used to block malware and other content that is or contains hostile, intrusive, or annoying material including adware, spam, computer viruses, worms, trojan horses, and spyware.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] Most content control software is marketed to organizations or parents.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] It is, however, also marketed on occasion to facilitate self-censorship, for example by people struggling with addictions to online pornography, gambling, chat rooms, etc.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] Self-censorship software may also be utilised by some in order to avoid viewing content they consider immoral, inappropriate, or simply distracting.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] A number of accountability software products are marketed as *self-censorship* or *accountability software*.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] These are often promoted by religious media and at religious gatherings.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] Content filtering technology exists in two major forms: application gateway or packet inspection.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] For HTTP access the application gateway is called a web-proxy or just a proxy.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] Such web-proxies can inspect both the initial request and the returned web page using arbitrarily complex rules and will not return any part of the page to the requester until a decision is made.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] In addition they can make substitutions in whole or for any part of the returned result.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] Packet inspection filters do not initially interfere with the connection to the server but inspect the data in the connection as it goes past, at some point the filter may decide that the connection is to be filtered and it will then disconnect it by injecting a TCP-Reset or similar faked packet.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] The two techniques can be used together with the packet filter monitoring a link until it sees an HTTP connection starting to an IP address that has content that needs filtering.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] The packet filter then redirects the connection to the web-proxy which can perform detailed filtering on the website without having to pass through all unfiltered connections.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] This combination is quite popular because it can significantly reduce the cost of the system.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] There are constraints to IP level packet-filtering, as it may result in rendering all web content associated with a particular IP address inaccessible.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] This may result in the unintentional blocking of legitimate sites that share the same IP address or domain.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] For instance, university websites commonly employ multiple domains under one IP address.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] Moreover, IP level packet-filtering can be surpassed by using a distinct IP address for certain content while still being linked to the same domain or server.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] Gateway-based content control software may be more difficult to bypass than desktop software as the user does not have physical access to the filtering device.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] However, many of the techniques in the Bypassing filters section still work.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] Content labeling may be considered another form of content-control software.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] In 1994, the Internet Content Rating Association (ICRA) — now part of the Family Online Safety Institute — developed a content rating system for online content providers.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] Using an online questionnaire a webmaster describes the nature of their web content.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] A small file is generated that contains a condensed, computer readable digest of this description that can then be used by content filtering software to block or allow that site.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] ICRA labels come in a variety of formats.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] These include the World Wide Web Consortium's Resource Description Framework (RDF) as well as Platform for Internet Content Selection (PICS) labels used by Microsoft's Internet Explorer Content Advisor.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] ICRA labels are an example of self-labeling.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] Similarly, in 2006 the Association of Sites Advocating Child Protection (ASACP) initiated the Restricted to Adults self-labeling initiative.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] ASACP members were concerned that various forms of legislation being proposed in the United States were going to have the effect of forcing adult companies to label their content.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] The RTA label, unlike ICRA labels, does not require a webmaster to fill out a questionnaire or sign up to use.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] Both labels are recognized by a wide variety of content-control software.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] The Voluntary Content Rating (VCR) system was devised by Solid Oak Software for their CYBERsitter filtering software, as an alternative to the PICS system, which some critics deemed too complex.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] It employs HTML metadata tags embedded within web page documents to specify the type of content contained in the document.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] Only two levels are specified, *mature* and *adult*, making the specification extremely simple.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] The Australian Internet Safety Advisory Body has information about "practical advice on Internet safety, parental control and filters for the protection of children, students and families" that also includes public libraries.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] NetAlert, the software made available free of charge by the Australian government, was allegedly cracked by a 16-year-old student, Tom Wood, less than a week after its release in August 2007.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] Wood supposedly bypassed the $84 million filter in about half an hour to highlight problems with the government's approach to Internet content filtering.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] The Australian Government has introduced legislation that requires ISPs to "restrict access to age restricted content (commercial MA15+ content and R18+ content) either hosted in Australia or provided from Australia" that was due to commence from 20 January 2008, known as Cleanfeed.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] Cleanfeed is a proposed mandatory ISP level content filtration system.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] It was proposed by the Beazley led Australian Labor Party opposition in a 2006 press release, with the intention of protecting children who were vulnerable due to claimed parental computer illiteracy.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] It was announced on 31 December 2007 as a policy to be implemented by the Rudd ALP government, and initial tests in Tasmania have produced a 2008 report.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] Cleanfeed is funded in the current budget, and is moving towards an Expression of Interest for live testing with ISPs in 2008.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] Public opposition and criticism have emerged, led by the EFA and gaining irregular mainstream media attention, with a majority of Australians reportedly "strongly against" its implementation.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] Criticisms include its expense, inaccuracy (it will be impossible to ensure only illegal sites are blocked) and the fact that it will be compulsory, which can be seen as an intrusion on free speech rights.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] Another major criticism point has been that although the filter is claimed to stop certain materials, the underground rings dealing in such materials will not be affected.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] The filter might also provide a false sense of security for parents, who might supervise children less while using the Internet, achieving the exact opposite effect.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] Cleanfeed is a responsibility of Senator Conroy's portfolio.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] In Denmark it is stated policy that it will "prevent inappropriate Internet sites from being accessed from children's libraries across Denmark".
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] "'It is important that every library in the country has the opportunity to protect children against pornographic material when they are using library computers.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] Many libraries in the UK such as the British Library and local authority public libraries apply filters to Internet access.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] According to research conducted by the Radical Librarians Collective, at least 98% of public libraries apply filters; including categories such as "LGBT interest", "abortion" and "questionable".
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] The use of Internet filters or content-control software varies widely in public libraries in the United States, since Internet use policies are established by the local library board.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] Many libraries adopted Internet filters after Congress conditioned the receipt of universal service discounts on the use of Internet filters through the Children's Internet Protection Act (CIPA).
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] Other libraries do not install content control software, believing that acceptable use policies and educational efforts address the issue of children accessing age-inappropriate content while preserving adult users' right to freely access information.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] Some libraries use Internet filters on computers used by children only.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] Many legal scholars believe that a number of legal cases, in particular *Reno v.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] American Civil Liberties Union*, established that the use of content-control software in libraries is a violation of the First Amendment.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] The Children's Internet Protection Act [CIPA] and the June 2003 case *United States v.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] The plurality decision left open a future "as-applied" Constitutional challenge, however.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] In November 2006, a lawsuit was filed against the North Central Regional Library District (NCRL) in Washington State for its policy of refusing to disable restrictions upon requests of adult patrons, but CIPA was not challenged in that matter.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] The Court said: "It appears to us that NCRL's filtering policy is reasonable and accords with its mission and these policies and is viewpoint neutral.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] It appears that no article I, section 5 content-based violation exists in this case.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] NCRL's essential mission is to promote reading and lifelong learning.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] As NCRL maintains, it is reasonable to impose restrictions on Internet access in order to maintain an environment that is conducive to study and contemplative thought." The case returned to federal court.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] In March 2007, Virginia passed a law similar to CIPA that requires public libraries receiving state funds to use content-control software.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] Like CIPA, the law requires libraries to disable filters for an adult library user when requested to do so by the user.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] Utilizing a filter that is overly zealous at filtering content, or mislabels content not intended to be censored can result in over-blocking, or over-censoring.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] Overblocking can filter out material that should be acceptable under the filtering policy in effect, for example health related information may unintentionally be filtered along with porn-related material because of the Scunthorpe problem.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] Filter administrators may prefer to err on the side of caution by accepting over blocking to prevent any risk of access to sites that they determine to be undesirable.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] Content-control software was mentioned as blocking access to Beaver College before its name change to Arcadia University.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] Another example was the filtering of Horniman Museum.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] As well, over-blocking may encourage users to bypass the filter entirely.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] Whenever new information is uploaded to the Internet, filters can under block, or under-censor, content if the parties responsible for maintaining the filters do not update them quickly and accurately, and a blacklisting rather than a whitelisting filtering policy is in place.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] Many would not be satisfied with government filtering viewpoints on moral or political issues, agreeing that this could become support for propaganda.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] Many would also find it unacceptable that an ISP, whether by law or by the ISP's own choice, should deploy such software without allowing the users to disable the filtering for their own connections.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] In the United States, the First Amendment to the United States Constitution has been cited in calls to criminalise forced internet censorship.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] Many types of content-control software have been shown to block sites based on the religious and political leanings of the company owners.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] Examples include blocking several religious sites (including the Web site of the Vatican), many political sites, and homosexuality-related sites.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] *X-Stop* was shown to block sites such as the Quaker web site, the National Journal of Sexual Orientation Law, The Heritage Foundation, and parts of The Ethical Spectacle.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] CYBERsitter blocks out sites like National Organization for Women.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] Nancy Willard, an academic researcher and attorney, pointed out that many U.S. public schools and libraries use the same filtering software that many Christian organizations use.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] In 1998, a United States federal district court in Virginia ruled (Loudoun v.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] Board of Trustees of the Loudoun County Library) that the imposition of mandatory filtering in a public library violates the First Amendment.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] In 1996 the US Congress passed the Communications Decency Act, banning indecency on the Internet.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] Civil liberties groups challenged the law under the First Amendment, and in 1997 the Supreme Court ruled in their favor.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] Part of the civil liberties argument, especially from groups like the Electronic Frontier Foundation, was that parents who wanted to block sites could use their own content-filtering software, making government involvement unnecessary.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] In the late 1990s, groups such as the Censorware Project began reverse-engineering the content-control software and decrypting the blacklists to determine what kind of sites the software blocked.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] This led to legal action alleging violation of the "Cyber Patrol" license agreement.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] They discovered that such tools routinely blocked unobjectionable sites while also failing to block intended targets.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] Some content-control software companies responded by claiming that their filtering criteria were backed by intensive manual checking.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] The companies' opponents argued, on the other hand, that performing the necessary checking would require resources greater than the companies possessed and that therefore their claims were not valid.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] The Motion Picture Association successfully obtained a UK ruling enforcing ISPs to use content-control software to prevent copyright infringement by their subscribers.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] Content filtering in general can "be bypassed entirely by tech-savvy individuals." Blocking content on a device "[will not]…guarantee that users won't eventually be able to find a way around the filter." Content providers may change URLs or IP addresses to circumvent filtering.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] Individuals with technical expertise may use a different method by employing multiple domains or URLs that direct to a shared IP address where restricted content is present.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] This strategy doesn't circumvent IP packet filtering, however can evade DNS poisoning and web proxies.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] Additionally, perpetrators may use mirrored websites that avoid filters.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] Some software may be bypassed successfully by using alternative protocols such as FTP or telnet or HTTPS, conducting searches in a different language, using a proxy server or a circumventor such as Psiphon.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] Also cached web pages returned by Google or other searches could bypass some controls as well.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] Web syndication services may provide alternate paths for content.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] Some of the more poorly designed programs can be shut down by killing their processes: for example, in Microsoft Windows through the Windows Task Manager, or in Mac OS X using Force Quit or Activity Monitor.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] Numerous workarounds and counters to workarounds from content-control software creators exist.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] Google services are often blocked by filters, but these may most often be bypassed by using *https://* in place of *http://* since content filtering software is not able to interpret content under secure connections (in this case SSL).
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] An encrypted VPN can be used as means of bypassing content control software, especially if the content control software is installed on an Internet gateway or firewall.
[src:next-gen-firewall/content-control-software] Other ways to bypass a content control filter include translation sites and establishing a remote connection with an uncensored device.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] An **intrusion detection system** (**IDS**) is a device or software application that monitors a network or systems for malicious activity or policy violations.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] Any intrusion activity or violation is typically either reported to an administrator or collected centrally using a security information and event management (SIEM) system.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] A SIEM system combines outputs from multiple sources and uses alarm filtering techniques to distinguish malicious activity from false alarms.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] IDS types range in scope from single computers to large networks.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] The most common classifications are **network intrusion detection systems** (**NIDS**) and **host-based intrusion detection systems** (**HIDS**).
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] A system that monitors important operating system files is an example of an HIDS, while a system that analyzes incoming network traffic is an example of an NIDS.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] It is also possible to classify IDS by detection approach.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] The most well-known variants are signature-based detection (recognizing bad patterns, such as exploitation attempts) and anomaly-based detection (detecting deviations from a model of "good" traffic, which often relies on machine learning).
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] Another common variant is reputation-based detection (recognizing the potential threat according to the reputation scores).
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] Some IDS products have the ability to respond to detected intrusions.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] Systems with response capabilities are typically referred to as an **intrusion prevention system** (**IPS**).
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] Intrusion detection systems can also serve specific purposes by augmenting them with custom tools, such as using a honeypot to attract and characterize malicious traffic.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] Although they both relate to network security, an IDS differs from a firewall in that a conventional network firewall (distinct from a next-generation firewall) uses a static set of rules to permit or deny network connections.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] It implicitly prevents intrusions, assuming an appropriate set of rules have been defined.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] Essentially, firewalls limit access between networks to prevent intrusion and do not signal an attack from inside the network.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] An IDS describes a suspected intrusion once it has taken place and signals an alarm.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] An IDS also watches for attacks that originate from within a system.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] This is traditionally achieved by examining network communications, identifying heuristics and patterns (often known as signatures) of common computer attacks, and taking action to alert operators.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] A system that terminates connections is called an intrusion prevention system, and performs access control like an application layer firewall.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] IDS can be classified by where detection takes place (network or host) or the detection method that is employed (signature or anomaly-based).
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] Network intrusion detection systems (NIDS) are placed at a strategic point or points within the network to monitor traffic to and from all devices on the network.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] It performs an analysis of passing traffic on the entire subnet, and matches the traffic that is passed on the subnets to the library of known attacks.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] Once an attack is identified, or abnormal behavior is sensed, the alert can be sent to the administrator.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] NIDS function to safeguard every device and the entire network from unauthorized access.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] An example of an NIDS would be installing it on the subnet where firewalls are located in order to see if someone is trying to break into the firewall.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] Ideally one would scan all inbound and outbound traffic, however doing so might create a bottleneck that would impair the overall speed of the network.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] OPNET and NetSim are commonly used tools for simulating network intrusion detection systems.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] NID Systems are also capable of comparing signatures for similar packets to link and drop harmful detected packets which have a signature matching the records in the NIDS.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] When we classify the design of the NIDS according to the system interactivity property, there are two types: on-line and off-line NIDS, often referred to as inline and tap mode, respectively.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] On-line NIDS deals with the network in real time.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] It analyses the Ethernet packets and applies some rules, to decide if it is an attack or not.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] Off-line NIDS deals with stored data and passes it through some processes to decide if it is an attack or not.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] NIDS can be also combined with other technologies to increase detection and prediction rates.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] Artificial Neural Network (ANN) based IDS are capable of analyzing huge volumes of data due to the hidden layers and non-linear modeling, however this process requires time due its complex structure.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] This allows IDS to more efficiently recognize intrusion patterns.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] Neural networks assist IDS in predicting attacks by learning from mistakes; ANN based IDS help develop an early warning system, based on two layers.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] The first layer accepts single values, while the second layer takes the first's layers output as input; the cycle repeats and allows the system to automatically recognize new unforeseen patterns in the network.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] This system can average 99.9% detection and classification rate, based on research results of 24 network attacks, divided in four categories: DOS, Probe, Remote-to-Local, and user-to-root.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] Host intrusion detection systems (HIDS) run on individual hosts or devices on the network.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] A HIDS monitors the inbound and outbound packets from the device only and will alert the user or administrator if suspicious activity is detected.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] It takes a snapshot of existing system files and matches it to the previous snapshot.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] If the critical system files were modified or deleted, an alert is sent to the administrator to investigate.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] An example of HIDS usage can be seen on mission critical machines, which are not expected to change their configurations.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] Signature-based IDS is the detection of attacks by looking for specific patterns, such as byte sequences in network traffic, or known malicious instruction sequences used by malware.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] This terminology originates from anti-virus software, which refers to these detected patterns as signatures.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] Although signature-based IDS can easily detect known attacks, it is difficult to detect new attacks, for which no pattern is available.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] In signature-based IDS, the signatures are released by a vendor for all its products.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] On-time updating of the IDS with the signature is a key aspect.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] Anomaly-based intrusion detection systems were primarily introduced to detect unknown attacks, in part due to the rapid development of malware.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] The basic approach is to use machine learning to create a model of trustworthy activity, and then compare new behavior against this model.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] Since these models can be trained according to the applications and hardware configurations, machine learning based method has a better generalized property in comparison to traditional signature-based IDS.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] Although this approach enables the detection of previously unknown attacks, it may suffer from false positives: previously unknown legitimate activity may also be classified as malicious.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] Most of the existing IDSs suffer from the time-consuming during detection process that degrades the performance of IDSs.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] Efficient feature selection algorithm makes the classification process used in detection more reliable.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] Recent research has also explored deep learning approaches for anomaly-based intrusion detection, as these methods can learn complex traffic patterns and help identify previously unseen attacks more effectively.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] New types of what could be called anomaly-based intrusion detection systems are being viewed by Gartner as User and Entity Behavior Analytics (UEBA) (an evolution of the user behavior analytics category) and network traffic analysis (NTA).
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] In particular, NTA deals with malicious insiders as well as targeted external attacks that have compromised a user machine or account.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] Gartner has noted that some organizations have opted for NTA over more traditional IDS.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] Some systems may attempt to stop an intrusion attempt but this is neither required nor expected of a monitoring system.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] Intrusion detection and prevention systems (IDPS) are primarily focused on identifying possible incidents, logging information about them, and reporting attempts.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] In addition, organizations use IDPS for other purposes, such as identifying problems with security policies, documenting existing threats and deterring individuals from violating security policies.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] IDPS have become a necessary addition to the security infrastructure of nearly every organization.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] IDPS typically record information related to observed events, notify security administrators of important observed events and produce reports.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] Many IDPS can also respond to a detected threat by attempting to prevent it from succeeding.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] They use several response techniques, which involve the IDPS stopping the attack itself, changing the security environment (e.g. reconfiguring a firewall) or changing the attack's content.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] Intrusion prevention systems are considered extensions of intrusion detection systems because they both monitor network traffic and/or system activities for malicious activity.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] The main differences are, unlike intrusion detection systems, intrusion prevention systems are placed in-line and are able to actively prevent or block intrusions that are detected.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] IPS can take such actions as sending an alarm, dropping detected malicious packets, resetting a connection or blocking traffic from the offending IP address.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] An IPS also can correct cyclic redundancy check (CRC) errors, defragment packet streams, mitigate TCP sequencing issues, and clean up unwanted transport and network layer options.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] **Wireless intrusion prevention system (WIPS)**: monitor a wireless network for suspicious traffic by analyzing wireless networking protocols.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] **Network behavior analysis (NBA)**: examines network traffic to identify threats that generate unusual traffic flows, such as distributed denial of service (DDoS) attacks, certain forms of malware and policy violations.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] **Host-based intrusion prevention system (HIPS)**: an installed software package which monitors a single host for suspicious activity by analyzing events occurring within that host.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] The majority of intrusion prevention systems utilize one of three detection methods: signature-based, statistical anomaly-based, and stateful protocol analysis.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] **Statistical anomaly-based detection**: An IDS which is anomaly-based will monitor network traffic and compare it against an established baseline.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] The baseline will identify what is "normal" for that network – what sort of bandwidth is generally used and what protocols are used.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] It may however, raise a False Positive alarm for legitimate use of bandwidth if the baselines are not intelligently configured.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] Ensemble models that use Matthews correlation co-efficient to identify unauthorized network traffic have obtained 99.73% accuracy.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] **Stateful protocol analysis detection**: This method identifies deviations of protocol states by comparing observed events with "pre-determined profiles of generally accepted definitions of benign activity".
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] While it is capable of knowing and tracing the protocol states, it requires significant resources.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] The correct placement of intrusion detection systems is critical and varies depending on the network.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] The most common placement is behind the firewall, on the edge of a network.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] This practice provides the IDS with high visibility of traffic entering your network and will not receive any traffic between users on the network.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] The edge of the network is the point in which a network connects to the extranet.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] If an IDS is placed beyond a network's firewall, its main purpose would be to defend against noise from the internet but, more importantly, defend against common attacks, such as port scans and network mapper.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] An IDS in this position would monitor layers 4 through 7 of the OSI model and would be signature-based.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] This is a very useful practice, because rather than showing actual breaches into the network that made it through the firewall, attempted breaches will be shown which reduces the amount of false positives.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] The IDS in this position also assists in decreasing the amount of time it takes to discover successful attacks against a network.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] Sometimes an IDS with more advanced features will be integrated with a firewall in order to be able to intercept sophisticated attacks entering the network.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] Examples of advanced features would include multiple security contexts in the routing level and bridging mode.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] All of this in turn potentially reduces cost and operational complexity.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] Another option for IDS placement is within the actual network.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] These will reveal attacks or suspicious activity within the network.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] Ignoring the security within a network can cause many problems, it will either allow users to bring about security risks or allow an attacker who has already broken into the network to roam around freely.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] Intense intranet security makes it difficult for even those hackers within the network to maneuver around and escalate their privileges.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] The earliest preliminary IDS concept was delineated in 1980 by James Anderson at the National Security Agency and consisted of a set of tools intended to help administrators review audit trails.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] User access logs, file access logs, and system event logs are examples of audit trails.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] Fred Cohen noted in 1987 that it is impossible to detect an intrusion in every case, and that the resources needed to detect intrusions grow with the amount of usage.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] Neumann, published a model of an IDS in 1986 that formed the basis for many systems today.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] Her model used statistics for anomaly detection, and resulted in an early IDS at SRI International named the Intrusion Detection Expert System (IDES), which ran on Sun workstations and could consider both user and network level data.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] IDES had a dual approach with a rule-based Expert System to detect known types of intrusions plus a statistical anomaly detection component based on profiles of users, host systems, and target systems.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] The author of "IDES: An Intelligent System for Detecting Intruders", Teresa F.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] Lunt, proposed adding an artificial neural network as a third component.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] She said all three components could then report to a resolver.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] SRI followed IDES in 1993 with the Next-generation Intrusion Detection Expert System (NIDES).
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] The Multics intrusion detection and alerting system (MIDAS), an expert system using P-BEST and Lisp, was developed in 1988 based on the work of Denning and Neumann.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] Haystack was also developed in that year using statistics to reduce audit trails.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] In 1986 the National Security Agency started an IDS research transfer program under Rebecca Bace.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] Bace later published the seminal text on the subject, *Intrusion Detection*, in 2000.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] Wisdom & Sense (W&S) was a statistics-based anomaly detector developed in 1989 at the Los Alamos National Laboratory.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] W&S created rules based on statistical analysis, and then used those rules for anomaly detection.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] In 1990, the Time-based Inductive Machine (TIM) did anomaly detection using inductive learning of sequential user patterns in Common Lisp on a VAX 3500 computer.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] The Network Security Monitor (NSM) performed masking on access matrices for anomaly detection on a Sun-3/50 workstation.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] The Information Security Officer's Assistant (ISOA) was a 1990 prototype that considered a variety of strategies including statistics, a profile checker, and an expert system.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] ComputerWatch at AT&T Bell Labs used statistics and rules for audit data reduction and intrusion detection.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] Then, in 1991, researchers at the University of California, Davis created a prototype Distributed Intrusion Detection System (DIDS), which was also an expert system.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] The Network Anomaly Detection and Intrusion Reporter (NADIR), also in 1991, was a prototype IDS developed at the Los Alamos National Laboratory's Integrated Computing Network (ICN), and was heavily influenced by the work of Denning and Lunt.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] NADIR used a statistics-based anomaly detector and an expert system.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] The Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory announced Bro in 1998, which used its own rule language for packet analysis from libpcap data.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] Network Flight Recorder (NFR) in 1999 also used libpcap.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] APE was developed as a packet sniffer, also using libpcap, in November, 1998, and was renamed Snort one month later.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] Snort has since become the world's largest used IDS/IPS system with over 300,000 active users.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] It can monitor both local systems, and remote capture points using the TZSP protocol.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] The Audit Data Analysis and Mining (ADAM) IDS in 2001 used tcpdump to build profiles of rules for classifications.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] In 2003, Yongguang Zhang and Wenke Lee argue for the importance of IDS in networks with mobile nodes.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] In 2015, Viegas and his colleagues proposed an anomaly-based intrusion detection engine, aiming System-on-Chip (SoC) for applications in Internet of Things (IoT), for instance.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] The proposal applies machine learning for anomaly detection, providing energy-efficiency to a Decision Tree, Naive-Bayes, and k-Nearest Neighbors classifiers implementation in an Atom CPU and its hardware-friendly implementation in a FPGA.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] In the literature, this was the first work that implement each classifier equivalently in software and hardware and measures its energy consumption on both.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] Additionally, it was the first time that was measured the energy consumption for extracting each features used to make the network packet classification, implemented in software and hardware.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] Several regulatory frameworks require or recommend intrusion detection capabilities as part of information security compliance.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] In the United States, the Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act (HIPAA) Security Rule requires covered entities to implement procedures for monitoring log-in attempts and reporting discrepancies as part of their information system activity review.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] The December 2024 Notice of proposed rulemaking (NPRM) to overhaul the HIPAA Security Rule would explicitly mandate deployment of intrusion detection and intrusion prevention systems, along with continuous monitoring of all information systems containing electronic protected health information.
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] The Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard (PCI DSS) requires the use of intrusion detection or intrusion prevention techniques to detect or prevent intrusions into networks handling cardholder data (Requirement 11.5).
[src:next-gen-firewall/intrusion-prevention-system] The National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) SP 800-53 includes the SI-4 (Information System Monitoring) control family, which specifies intrusion detection as a core capability for federal information systems.
[src:next-gen-firewall/next-generation-firewall] A **next-generation firewall** (**NGFW**) is a part of the third generation of firewall technology, combining a conventional firewall with other network device filtering functions, such as an application firewall using in-line deep packet inspection (DPI) and an intrusion prevention system (IPS).
[src:next-gen-firewall/next-generation-firewall] Other techniques might also be employed, such as TLS-encrypted traffic inspection, website filtering, QoS/bandwidth management, antivirus inspection, third-party identity management integration (e.g.
[src:next-gen-firewall/next-generation-firewall] LDAP, RADIUS, Active Directory), and SSL decryption.
[src:next-gen-firewall/next-generation-firewall] **Unified Threat Management** refers to a similar appliance as an NGFW.
[src:next-gen-firewall/next-generation-firewall] One of the first mentions of the NGFW term was in a 2004 document by Gartner.
[src:next-gen-firewall/next-generation-firewall] Kenneth Tam speculated that the term Unified Threat Management (UTM) was coined by IDC because they did not want to adopt the name of their competitor.
[src:next-gen-firewall/next-generation-firewall] NGFWs include the typical functions of traditional firewalls such as packet filtering, network- and port-address translation (NAT), stateful inspection, and virtual private network (VPN) support.
[src:next-gen-firewall/next-generation-firewall] The goal of next-generation firewalls is to include more layers of the OSI model, improving filtering of network traffic that is dependent on the packet contents.
[src:next-gen-firewall/next-generation-firewall] The most significant differences are that NGFWs include intrusion prevention systems (IPS) and application control.
[src:next-gen-firewall/next-generation-firewall] Next-generation firewalls perform deeper inspection compared to stateful inspection performed by the first- and second-generation firewalls.
[src:next-gen-firewall/next-generation-firewall] NGFWs use a more thorough inspection style, checking packet payloads and matching signatures for harmful activities such as exploitable attacks and malware.
[src:next-gen-firewall/next-generation-firewall] Modern threats like web-based malware attacks, targeted attacks, application-layer attacks, and more have had a significantly negative effect on the threat landscape.
[src:next-gen-firewall/next-generation-firewall] In fact, one in four attacks exploit vulnerabilities in public-facing applications, as opposed to weaknesses in networking components and services.
[src:next-gen-firewall/next-generation-firewall] Stateful firewalls with simple packet filtering capabilities were efficient blocking unwanted applications as most applications met the port-protocol expectations.
[src:next-gen-firewall/next-generation-firewall] Administrators could promptly prevent an unsafe application from being accessed by users by blocking the associated ports and protocols.
[src:next-gen-firewall/next-generation-firewall] But blocking a web application that uses port 80 by closing the port would also mean complications with the entire HTTP protocol.
[src:next-gen-firewall/next-generation-firewall] Protection based on ports, protocols, IP addresses is no more reliable and viable.
[src:next-gen-firewall/next-generation-firewall] This has led to the development of identity-based security approach, which takes organizations a step ahead of conventional security appliances which bind security to IP-addresses.
[src:next-gen-firewall/next-generation-firewall] NGFWs offer administrators a deeper awareness of and control over individual applications, along with deeper inspection capabilities by the firewall.
[src:next-gen-firewall/next-generation-firewall] Administrators can create very granular "allow/deny" rules for controlling use of websites and applications in the network.
[src:next-gen-firewall/stateful-firewall] In computing, a **stateful firewall** is a network-based firewall that individually tracks sessions of network connections traversing it.
[src:next-gen-firewall/stateful-firewall] **Stateful packet inspection**, also referred to as dynamic packet filtering, is a security feature often used in non-commercial and business networks.
[src:next-gen-firewall/stateful-firewall] A stateful firewall keeps track of the state of network connections, such as TCP streams, UDP datagrams, and ICMP messages, and can apply labels such as *LISTEN*, *ESTABLISHED*, or *CLOSING*.
[src:next-gen-firewall/stateful-firewall] State table entries are created for TCP streams or UDP datagrams that are allowed to communicate through the firewall in accordance with the configured security policy.
[src:next-gen-firewall/stateful-firewall] Once in the table, all *RELATED* packets of a stored session are streamlined, taking fewer CPU cycles than standard inspection.
[src:next-gen-firewall/stateful-firewall] Related packets are also permitted to return through the firewall even if no rule is configured to allow communications from that host.
[src:next-gen-firewall/stateful-firewall] If no traffic is seen for a specified time (time-out implementation dependent), the connection is removed from the state table.
[src:next-gen-firewall/stateful-firewall] This can lead to applications experiencing unexpected disconnects or half-open TCP connections.
[src:next-gen-firewall/stateful-firewall] Applications can be written to send keepalive messages periodically to prevent a firewall from dropping the connection during periods of no activity or for applications which by design have long periods of silence.
[src:next-gen-firewall/stateful-firewall] The method of maintaining a session's state depends on the transport protocol being used.
[src:next-gen-firewall/stateful-firewall] TCP is a connection-oriented protocol and sessions are established with a three-way handshake using *SYN* packets and ended by sending a *FIN* notification.
[src:next-gen-firewall/stateful-firewall] The firewall can use these unique connection identifiers to know when to remove a session from the state table without waiting for a timeout.
[src:next-gen-firewall/stateful-firewall] UDP is a connectionless protocol, which means it does not send unique connection-related identifiers while communicating.
[src:next-gen-firewall/stateful-firewall] Because of that, a session will only be removed from the state table after the configured time-out.
[src:next-gen-firewall/stateful-firewall] UDP hole punching is a technology that leverages this trait to allow for dynamically setting up data tunnels over the internet.
[src:next-gen-firewall/stateful-firewall] ICMP messages are distinct from TCP and UDP and communicate control information of the network itself.
[src:next-gen-firewall/stateful-firewall] A well-known example of this is the ping utility.
[src:next-gen-firewall/stateful-firewall] ICMP responses will be allowed back through the firewall.
[src:next-gen-firewall/stateful-firewall] In some scenarios, UDP communication can use ICMP to provide information about the state of the session so ICMP responses related to a UDP session will also be allowed back through.
[src:next-gen-firewall/web-application-firewall] A **Web application firewall** (**WAF**) is a specific form of application firewall that filters, monitors, and blocks HTTP traffic to and from a web service.
[src:next-gen-firewall/web-application-firewall] By inspecting HTTP traffic, it can prevent attacks exploiting a Web application's known vulnerabilities, such as SQL injection, cross-site scripting (XSS), file inclusion, and improper system configuration.
[src:next-gen-firewall/web-application-firewall] Financial institutions often utilize WAFs to help in the mitigation of Web application zero-day vulnerabilities, as well as hard-to-patch bugs or weaknesses through custom attack signature strings.
[src:next-gen-firewall/web-application-firewall] Dedicated Web application firewalls entered the market in the late 1990s during a time when web server attacks were becoming more prevalent.
[src:next-gen-firewall/web-application-firewall] Early WAF products, from Kavado and Gilian technologies, tried to solve the increasing amount of attacks on Web applications in the late 1990s.
[src:next-gen-firewall/web-application-firewall] In 2002, the open-source project ModSecurity was formed in order to make WAF technology more accessible.
[src:next-gen-firewall/web-application-firewall] They finalized a core rule set for protecting Web applications, based on OASIS Web Application Security Technical Committee’s (WAS TC) vulnerability work.
[src:next-gen-firewall/web-application-firewall] In 2003, they expanded and standardized rules through the Open Web Application Security Project’s (OWASP) Top 10 List, an annual ranking for Web security vulnerabilities.
[src:next-gen-firewall/web-application-firewall] This list would become the industry standard for Web application security compliance.
[src:next-gen-firewall/web-application-firewall] Since then, the market has continued to grow and evolve, especially focusing on credit card fraud prevention.
[src:next-gen-firewall/web-application-firewall] With the development of the Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard (PCI DSS), a standardization of control over cardholder data, security has become more regulated in this sector.
[src:next-gen-firewall/web-application-firewall] A Web application firewall is a special type of application firewall that applies specifically to Web applications.
[src:next-gen-firewall/web-application-firewall] It is deployed in front of Web applications and analyzes bi-directional web-based (HTTP) traffic – detecting and blocking anything malicious.
[src:next-gen-firewall/web-application-firewall] The OWASP provides a broad technical definition for a WAF as “a security solution on the Web application level which – from a technical point of view – does not depend on the application itself”.
[src:next-gen-firewall/web-application-firewall] According to the PCI DSS Information Supplement for requirement 6.6, a WAF is defined as “a security policy enforcement point positioned between a Web application and the client endpoint.
[src:next-gen-firewall/web-application-firewall] This functionality can be implemented in software or hardware, running in an appliance device, or in a typical server running a common operating system.
[src:next-gen-firewall/web-application-firewall] It may be a stand-alone device or integrated into other network components.” In other words, a WAF can be a virtual or physical appliance that prevents vulnerabilities in Web applications from being exploited by outside threats.
[src:next-gen-firewall/web-application-firewall] These vulnerabilities may be because the application itself is a legacy type or was insufficiently coded by design.
[src:next-gen-firewall/web-application-firewall] The WAF addresses these code shortcomings by special configurations of rule-sets, also known as policies.
[src:next-gen-firewall/web-application-firewall] Previously unknown vulnerabilities can be discovered through penetration testing or via a vulnerability scanner.
[src:next-gen-firewall/web-application-firewall] A Web application vulnerability scanner, also known as a web application security scanner, is defined in the SAMATE NIST 500-269 as “an automated program that examines Web applications for potential security vulnerabilities.
[src:next-gen-firewall/web-application-firewall] In addition to searching for Web application-specific vulnerabilities, the tools also look for software coding errors.” Resolving vulnerabilities is commonly referred to as remediation.
[src:next-gen-firewall/web-application-firewall] Corrections to the code can be made in the application, but typically a more prompt response is necessary.
[src:next-gen-firewall/web-application-firewall] In these situations, the application of a custom policy for a unique Web application vulnerability to provide a temporary but immediate fix (known as a virtual patch) may be necessary.
[src:next-gen-firewall/web-application-firewall] WAFs are not an ultimate security solution, rather they are meant to be used in conjunction with other network perimeter security solutions such as network firewalls and intrusion prevention systems to provide a holistic defense strategy.
[src:next-gen-firewall/web-application-firewall] WAFs typically follow a positive security model, a negative security, or a combination of both as mentioned by the SANS Institute.
[src:next-gen-firewall/web-application-firewall] WAFs use a combination of rule-based logic, parsing, and signatures to detect and prevent attacks such as cross-site scripting and SQL injection.
[src:next-gen-firewall/web-application-firewall] In general, features like browser emulation, obfuscation and virtualization, and IP obfuscation are used to attempt to bypass WAFs.
[src:next-gen-firewall/web-application-firewall] The OWASP produces a list of the top ten Web application security flaws.
[src:next-gen-firewall/web-application-firewall] All commercial WAF offerings cover these ten flaws at a minimum.
[src:next-gen-firewall/web-application-firewall] There are non-commercial options as well.
[src:next-gen-firewall/web-application-firewall] As mentioned earlier, the well-known open-source WAF engine called ModSecurity is one of these options.
[src:next-gen-firewall/web-application-firewall] A WAF engine alone is insufficient to provide adequate protection, therefore OWASP along with Trustwave's Spiderlabs help organize and maintain a Core-Rule Set via GitHub to use with the ModSecurity WAF engine.
[src:next-gen-firewall/web-application-firewall] Although the names for operating mode may differ, WAFs are basically deployed inline in three different ways.
[src:next-gen-firewall/web-application-firewall] According to NSS Labs, deployment options are transparent bridge, transparent reverse proxy, and reverse proxy.
[src:next-gen-firewall/web-application-firewall] "Transparent" refers to the fact that the HTTP traffic is sent straight to the Web application, therefore the WAF is transparent between the client and server.
[src:next-gen-firewall/web-application-firewall] This is in contrast to reverse proxy, where the WAF acts as a proxy, and the client’s traffic is sent directly to the WAF.
[src:next-gen-firewall/web-application-firewall] The WAF then separately sends filtered traffic to Web applications.
[src:next-gen-firewall/web-application-firewall] This can provide additional benefits such as IP masking but may introduce disadvantages such as performance latencies.
[src:next-gen-firewall/web-application-firewall] JA3, developed by Salesforce in 2017, is a technique for generating a unique fingerprint for SSL/TLS traffic based on specific fields in the handshake, such as the version, cipher suites, and extensions used by the client.
[src:next-gen-firewall/web-application-firewall] This fingerprint enables the identification and tracking of clients based on the characteristics of their encrypted traffic.
[src:next-gen-firewall/web-application-firewall] In the context of distributed denial of service (DDoS) protection, JA3 fingerprints are used to detect and differentiate malicious traffic, often associated with attack bots, from legitimate traffic, allowing for more precise filtering of potential threats.
[src:next-gen-firewall/web-application-firewall] In September 2023, AWS WAF announced built-in support for JA3, enabling customers to inspect the JA3 fingerprints of incoming requests.
[src:next-gen-firewall/web-application-firewall] JA3 was deprecated in May 2025 in favor of JA4.
